Bone histological analysis.
Most of the limb elements were poorly preserved in IVPP V24192; among these limb elements, we could extract only one sample from the left humerus for bone histological analysis (Extended Data 
Fig. 1a
). We also took a sample from the unidentified fragment preserved near the gastroliths (
Fig. 1
). The bone samples were embedded in one-component resin (EXAKT Technovit 7200) and hardened in a light polymerization device (EXAKT 520) for over 24 h. Thin cross-sections were cut using an accurate circular saw (EXAKT 300CP), and then were ground down using the EXAKT 400CS grinding system. The slides were ground to 40 µm—half the thickness that is typically necessary to visualize bone structure in similarly sized birds from the Jehol Biota—but the slides remained opaque.Images were taken using a digital camera (Zeiss AxioCam MRc5) under normal light (Zeiss AX10). Because of diagenetic alteration and breakage, the humeral cross-section provides little histological information; this information cannot be used to infer the ontogenetic stage of IVPP V24192 (Extended Data 
Fig. 2a, b
). Although also poorly preserved, the cross-section of the unidentified element shows that it is bone tissue (Extended Data 
Fig. 2c, d
).
